#{{note|tor}} That line was traspassed to U.N. Rodalies and now is considered a [[Rodalies Barcelona line 3]] enlargement.

===Railway stations===
{{Main|List of railway stations in Barcelona}}
{{double image|right|Fachada estaci<U+00F3>n de Sants.jpg|150|Estaci<U+00F3> de Fran<U+00E7>a Barcelona Catalonia.jpg|150|Two main railway stations of Barcelona: [[Barcelona Sants railway station]] and [[Barcelona Estaci<U+00F3> de Fran<U+00E7>a]].}}
There are currently 27 open railway stations in Barcelona (228 in the metropolitan area). The city's current main terminal station is [[Barcelona Sants]]. The construction of [[Estaci<U+00F3> de la Sagrera]], presently taking place in [[La Sagrera]] and designed by [[Frank Gehry]], will be a station of equal importance serving the other side of the city. Among other main stations, [[Estaci<U+00F3> de Fran<U+00E7>a]] has seen its importance reduced in the past years, and [[Estaci<U+00F3> del Nord Sports Hall|Estaci<U+00F3> del Nord]] (next to [[Arc de Triomf]]) is no longer a railway terminal but a coach station and athletic facility. [[El Clot-Arag<U+00F3>]] station was planned to be replaced by a new [[Gl<U+00F2>ries railway station]] at [[Pla<U+00E7>a de les Gl<U+00F2>ries Catalanes]] which would be one of the main transport hubs in the city when completed, but [[Pla<U+00E7>a de Catalunya railway station]], in the centre of Barcelona ([[Pla<U+00E7>a de Catalunya, Barcelona|Pla<U+00E7>a de Catalunya]]) is the only station in Barcelona where Renfe, FGC and Barcelona Metro lines join.

All [[Ferrocarrils de la Generalitat de Catalunya|FGC]] stations except for those between [[Peu del Funicular (FGC)|Peu del Funicular]] and [[Les Planes (FGC)|Les Planes]] also offer [[Barcelona Metro]] services, although trains operate every 6 minutes on workdays and 10 on weekdays, which is a better service than the L11 schedule.

==Barcelona Metro==
[[File:Met2.svg|thumb|Barcelona Metro map]]
[[File:Metro Barcelona Lesseps Station.jpg|thumb|[[Lesseps (Barcelona Metro)|Lesseps]] station]]
{{Main|Barcelona Metro}}
The Barcelona Metro, an electrified railway network, has served the city since 1924, when the [[Gran Metro (Barcelona)|Gran Metro]] and [[Metro Transversal (Barcelona)|Metro Transversal]]. The original project was devised in time for the [[1929 Universal Exhibition]] which took place in the city. Nowadays it is operated by two different companies: the proper metro lines being part of the [[Transports Metropolitans de Barcelona]] (or TMB) network, and three metro services integrated in the commuter railway network of [[Ferrocarrils de la Generalitat de Catalunya]] (or FGC), Catalonia's public railway company.

In addition to the eleven current working lines, the network is currently being expanded with the introduction of a double metro line which will be the longest in continental Europe: [[Barcelona Metro line 9|L9]]/[[Barcelona Metro line 10|L10]]. Nearly all existing lines are also growing, some extensively like [[Barcelona Metro line 2|L2]], and as of 2014 they are undergoing reforms.

As of January 2014, the metro network consists of:
