==Port of Barcelona==
{{Main|Port of Barcelona}}
[[File:BarcelonaHarbour.jpg|thumb|right|Port of Barcelona]]
The Port of Barcelona has a 2000-year history and a great contemporary commercial importance. It is Europe's ninth largest [[containerization|container]] port, with a trade volume of 2.3 million TEU's in 2006.<ref>{{Cite news| last =van Marle |first =Gavin |title =Europe terminals stretched to limit | work =[[Lloyd's List]] Daily Commercial News | pages =8<U+2013>9 | publisher =Informa Australia | date =31 January 2008}}</ref> The port is managed by the Port Authority of Barcelona. Its {{convert|7.86|km2|sqmi|0|abbr=on}} are divided into three zones: Port Vell (the Old Port), the commercial port and the logistics port ([[Barcelona Free Port]]). The port is undergoing an enlargement that will double its size thanks to diverting the mouth of the [[Llobregat]] river 2&nbsp;km (1<U+00BC>&nbsp;mi) to the south.<ref>[http://www.apb.es/wps/portal/!ut/p/c1/04_SB8K8xLLM9MSSzPy8xBz9CP0os_hgz2DDIFNLYwMLfzcDAyNjQy9vLwNTV38LM_1wkA6zeH_nIEcnJ0NHAwNfUxegCh8XA2-nUCMDdzOIvAEO4Gig7-eRn5uqX5CdneboqKgIAAeNRE8!/dl2/d1/L2dJQSEvUUt3QS9ZQnB3LzZfU0lTMVI1OTMwOE9GMDAyMzFKS0owNUVPODY!/?WCM_GLOBAL_CONTEXT=/wps/wcm/connect/ExtranetAnglesLib/El%20Port%20de%20Barcelona/el+port/historia+del+port/cami+cap+el+futur/ Port de Barcelona]</ref>

